---

`1-31`: **Consider adding prototype merging to the implementation.**

The current implementation only calls the constructors of both parent classes but doesn't merge their prototype methods and properties. For a complete multiple inheritance solution, you should also copy prototype methods.


You could enhance the `merge` function to also merge prototype methods:

```typescript
function merge<A extends ClassType, B extends ClassType>(
  a: A,
  b: B
): {
  new (def: ConstructorParameters<A>[0] & ConstructorParameters<B>[0]): A["prototype"] & B["prototype"];
} {
  // Create a new class
  const mergedClass = class {
    constructor(def: any) {
      a.call(this, def);
      b.call(this, def);
    }
  };

  // Copy prototype methods from both parent classes
  Object.getOwnPropertyNames(a.prototype).forEach(name => {
    if (name !== 'constructor') {
      mergedClass.prototype[name] = a.prototype[name];
    }
  });

  Object.getOwnPropertyNames(b.prototype).forEach(name => {
    if (name !== 'constructor') {
      mergedClass.prototype[name] = b.prototype[name];
    }
  });

  return mergedClass;
}
```

This would ensure that instances of the merged class have access to methods defined in both parent classes.

